"body":"Wait, that `spec=`... We should be using `spec=` on _every single Mock (of any flavor) in the program._ We know the types they're faking, right?","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":17,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-21T23:51:55Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970561130"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"To use a dictionary literal as a TypedDict, annotate the field type instead of using `cast`:\n```\nconfig: MafiaSchedulerConfig = {\n    \"mafia\": 1,\n    \"town\", 2,\n    #...\n}\n```\n\nOr use the constructor syntax:\n```\nconfig = MafiaSchedulerConfig(\n    mafia = 1,\n    town = 2,\n    role_Doctor = True,\n    # ...\n)\n```\n\nEither works, the dict literal is slightly more common but not much.\n\n`cast` defeats the type checker: it is a promise that the thing can be converted to this other type, and the type checker will take you at your word. You can use `typing.assert_type` instead of `typing.cast` -- annoyingly, `assert_type`'s parameters are in the exact opposite order of `cast`'s -- and then the static analyzer will complain if the conversion is illegal. But there is no need to do that here, because either of the two other syntaxes for explicitly pointing out that a dict should be interpreted as some specific TypedDict is available, with equivalent guarantees, and both of them are more common patterns for Python devs.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":37,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:01:33Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970577038"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Yeah, definitely pull this out to a common test helpers library, this is not the only thing that needs a mock TurnManager.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":42,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:02:14Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970578365"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"If you feel ambitious, the better way to do this (which would require a lot of tracing and test rewriting) would preserve _much_ more of the TurnManager:\n\n```\nclass TurnManagerWithMocks(turnmanager.TurnManager, typing.Protocol):\n    mock_chan: MagicMock\n    mock_bot: MagicMock\n\ndef make_test_turn_manager(players: list[Player], is_thread: bool = False) -\u003e TurnManagerWithMocks:\n    mock_chan = MagicMock(spec=discord.Thread if is_thread else discord.Channel)\n    mock_bot = MagicMock(spec=discord.Client)\n    ret = turnmanager.turnManager(players, mock_chan, mock_bot, None)\n    ret.mock_chan = mock_chan\n    ret.mock_bot = mock_bot\n    return cast(TurnManagerWithMocks, ret)\n```\n\nSome type checkers are smart enough to avoid the `cast`.\n\n`typing.Protocol` tells a type checker \"this is not a real type, this is just, like, the _shape_ of a category of type\". So the multiple-inheritance monstrosity is \"hey type checker, here is an idea of a type: a TurnManager with extra cheese\", a fair description of what `make_test_turn_manager` actually does. Because it's a Protocol, we have told the type checker to interpret this concept impressionistically (and type checkers actually capable of that can skip the cast in make_test_turn_manager).\n\nAnyway, this would give you a _real_ TurnManager talking to Fake Discord (and no OpenAI client; you might need to mock that out too), with the fake objects hastily duct-taped to the object before returning it so you can get at them in your tests (and we told the type checker about it so it will shut up when you try to actually use these fields).\n\nRight now, these tests treat TurnManager as a black box that it goes out of its way to avoid provoking. The more real objects you can get involved in the test, the more likely it is you'll catch real bugs -- but TurnManager's behavior is so complex it's definitely a pain to actually use in this way, so maybe a separate set of integration tests would be more appropriate. If TurnManager was less... itself... than it is, I would be more opinionated that you should avoid mocking it out entirely, but the code you have might genuinely be fine (other than \"you should only implement this once and use it everywhere you need a mock TurnManager\", that is).","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":48,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:29:16Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970603733"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"...`is_game_over` is a pretty bad name for this operation. Consider `who_won` instead.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":78,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:30:20Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970604466"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Oh, _that's_ how `is_game_over` is designed? ಠ_ಠ \n\n`None` would be a better return value in the real function. It's probably safe to just change it, since None is falsey -- as long as there aren't a lot of \"is False\" or \" == False\" checks that would be thrown off by it.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":109,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:31:54Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970605611"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Oof, I don't like this at all. You almost never want to mock out parts of the class under test. This once again pins down implementation details and makes it hard to verify that your tests actually _test_ anything. This tests the current \"shape\" of `run` in isolation, but...\n\nUgh. Is it feasible to create a more realistic scenario where mock inputs are at API boundaries and it effectively simulates an entire game? That may be a lot of work, but without It I'm skeptical of the value of this entire test. Mocking out the implementation of the class under test is a _very_ effective way to hide very serious bugs because your tests tend to look like they cover much more than they actually do, and once again it reifies \"implementation details\" into \"test expectation\".","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":133,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:37:05Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970609520"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Something went very, very wrong with formatting here.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":171,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:39:04Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970610901"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This also feels like it is heavily leaning on implementation details (although I recognize alternatives are likely to be annoying to write).","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":197,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:40:52Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970612203"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Is this a scenario that _should_ happen at all, or should this test be removed (and maybe `run_day_phase` should throw some kind of exception instead)?","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":219,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:43:17Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970613978"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This is 100% absolutely and purely testing an implementation detail. The important part is \"the right messages wind up on the right channels\". The \"set_channel\", \"set_participants\" calls are a means of doing so, not an outcome. Rewrite this to check that appropriate messages were sent to each channel.\n\nThis test verifies literally that \"set_channel\" and \"set_participants\" are called in various ways. It makes no particular statements about whether Mafia messages actually go to (only) the Mafia, which is the thing we actually care about.\n\nWriting the correct version of the test involves a lot of annoying, tedious tracing... or telling an AI about the real invariants you need to preserve and ask it to rewrite the test so it checks those rather than implementation details. A half-decent model can do that just fine when prompted, but the half-decent ones usually come up with chnage-detectors like _this_ when left to their own devices and the good models are only sometimes better at it. This is somewhere you get a lot of benefit out of AI but only when you pay attention rather than just let it do its thing.","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":250,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:50:16Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970618789"},{"body":"Recommendation: You probably want a fake \"set of channels\" object that can produce an itemized summary of what was sent. Something like this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nassert fake_chat.compute_conversation_state() == {\r\n    \"general_chat\": [(\"Mark\", \"Hi, I'm Mark!\"), (\"Lukas\", \"That's highly suspicious!\")]\r\n    \"scum_chat\": [(\"Lukas\", \"Mark is such a goofball!\")]\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nClaude will try very hard to avoid writing a simple `assert x == y` unless you give it a type that directly facilitates it and show it how that type would be used, so expect to have to write your first assertion yourself (or to have to tell it verbally that you want your code to look like the above.)","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":250,"author":"nyeogmi","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:58:03Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:58:03Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970707467"}],"total_count":2},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Yeah, this also needs to be sent through an auto-formatter or something...","path":"tests/classes/test_game.py","line":293,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:52:44Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T00:55:11Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970620473"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Ask the AI to check more than just the names here. Test is otherwise well-designed though.","path":"tests/classes/test_player.py","line":95,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T00:58:55Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970624987"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Also here, although it's less important if the other test is catching it since the codepath is likely to remain common.","path":"tests/classes/test_player.py","line":112,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:00:09Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970625623"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I'm pretty sure some of the other tests showed reasonably clearly that `abstractor` is lightweight enough it is feasible to use a real one (initialized with mocks), or am I misremembering?","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":25,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:02:21Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970627228"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Definitely pull these out into a more widely available test-util module of some kind, and add docstrings to clarify what is being mocked (subclasses of Discord, I believe). `spec=` in the mock declarations should help.","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":61,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:03:48Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970628053"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"It doesn't look like the order of anything shuffled actually gets _checked_ in this test, unless there's something very complicated I'm missing, so I don't think there's any good reason to patch out `random.shuffle`.","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":136,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:07:35Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970630785"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Also here. The _totals_ should be stable even if the exact assignments are randomized.","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":144,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:08:13Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970631183"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Etc. I'll stop repeating this comment but please clean it up everywhere the shuffle order isn't actually relevant to the test outcome.","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":154,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:08:43Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970631482"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"`setup_roles` does indeed do this, but _should_ it?","path":"tests/classes/test_scheduler.py","line":188,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:14:21Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970635343"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I genuinely have no idea what this is doing or why. Like, maybe it is absolutely, totally the right way to do this! whatever \"this\" is. But, uh, please add comments because this is getting into the _weird_ parts of Python even more than `unittest.mock` already does. Or get Claude to do it. (and keep an eye on it in future patches, Claude loves to delete comments)","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":20,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:36:47Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970650828"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This test currently does not distinguish between \"You cannot kick yourself.\" and \"hahaha u just kicked yourself dumbass\" and, for that matter, does not check whether `user` has genuinely not been, hypothetically, kicked.\n\nFrom `test_owner_kicks_player` we see that we can observe a kick, which means we can observe a non-kick. This test needs to pick up more of `test_owner_kicks_player`'s juju so we can verify that the player is still there.","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":35,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:43:53Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970656259"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"There is no specific test coverage for the situation where the owner, during a game in the channel specified, someone attempts to kick someone who does not exist, or someone who has already been kicked. I feel like these might be worth checking -- the \"already kicked\" thing could happen from a duplicated message, maybe a double-click in the UI faster than the server gets the message, etc., or just Discord being weird. The test should verify that, like `cannot_kick_self`, it doesn't actually accomplish much. (Although `cannot_kick_self` needs elaboration, because the test as written isn't complete enough to determine whether anyone _was_ actually (not) kicked, see below.)","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":29,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:45:40Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970657583"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I don't know why it's using `patch` as a local context manager in some spots and as a decorator in others, and for that matter `patch` in some spots and `monkeypatch` in others, but consistency makes a big difference to maintainability.","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":109,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:53:10Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970662769"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I remember from my romp through the code trying to verify Gemini's docstrings that `llama10` stood out to me as very unlikely to work as intended. I have not scrutinized these tests especially closely -- it looks like it's checking invariants that would actually work, but I think the command as a whole will put a game with a prior number of players unequal to 10 in an insane state with an unreasonable assignment of roles, especially if the game is ongoing? So if this test passes, but actually _using_ `/llama10` midgame crashes and burns, I think it's a useful illustration of the limits of tests -- this is indeed checking that you wind up with a game with 10 players in it, but it would be much more complicated to devise a test that determines that the game is still genuinely functional after you do so...\n\nOr maybe it works and I just did not understand the reasons it would work out okay! That is definitely also possible. But this doesn't seem to verify the game is meaningfully playable after the command, only who can use the command and how many players wind up in the game if the command succeeds. So if it _does_ work, test automation isn't preserving that, and if it is as broken as I think it might be, test automation isn't _detecting_ that if the tests pass this way. (But, committing tests that pass while code is in a broken state is a pretty common and reasonable dev strategy -- as long as it doesn't divert too much attention from whether the other aspects of the code are, themselves, correct.)","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":148,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:58:09Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970666196"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I observe no tests that expect `abstractor.game.running` to be `True`, so this test suite doesn't check that unauthorized users _can't_ stop the game.","path":"tests/cogs/test_games.py","line":151,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T01:59:05Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T02:00:24Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970666815"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These tests also assert error messages, but not that it didn't do the thing anyway!","path":"tests/cogs/test_moderation.py","line":38,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:25:25Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970684520"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Maybe \"does not create a webhook\" is one of the tools in your arsenal for \"did not do the thing\" for the other tests, btw.","path":"tests/cogs/test_moderation.py","line":65,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:26:01Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970684875"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"For all the fixtures in this file:\n\nFixture feels awkward. These are individual objects, not context that is getting set up and torn down in the tests. It's _very_ useful to have good, multi-trait mocks for these things -- there are a _lot_ of places I'd rather see functions reused rather than much weaker in-place MagicMock setups -- but a `@pytest.fixture` is a memoized singleton for its scope, they're not usable as \"normal functions\". Which is unfortunate, because as normal functions for repeated use these are pretty good!\n\nIf I was doing it by hand, I'd do the easy thing of rewriting each of these to a `new_mock_whatever` function, and then \"replace\" the fixture with its equivalent that just calls into `new_mock_whatever`, and then use the `new_mock_whatever` everywhere I want one in the future (and to replace existing in-place \"shoddy mocks\"), while tolerating the existing fixture uses but cleaning them up if I'm \"in\" that area anyway, with the intent of eventually deleting them.\n\nAn AI can be more ambitious and just do a mass cleanup. Up to you which approach you want to take. ","path":"tests/conftest.py","line":8,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:32:24Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970689494"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Oh, okay, my concerns about data being nonempty were false positives. cool!\n\nA better mock here could save a closed-over value, `last_data` that is initially `{}` at test start; `load` would retrieve a deep copy `last_data`, `save` overwrites it with a deep copy, using `lambda`s as the mock implementations for each of these. Then you have a much higher fidelity data fake; this one is equivalent to \"you cannot actually save anything ever, it just gets overwritten with a blank file no matter what\" which is useful for testing that `load` isn't actually important midgame, which admittedly might be a good idea because there are some issues with data consistency in the current implementation but, still, the higher-fidelity fake is _possibly_ useful. But the tests pass as-is, so it might not be worth the effort.\n\nI think the biggest reason to do it is that it increases the odds that additional tests will \"just work\", as opposed to leaving folks trying to figure out what's wrong with their save/load logic when _it's_ fine, but the test is too low-fidelity to recognize, and it might take a while to find out that this is interfering.\n\nIf you leave this as-is, I strongly recommend adding a warning about it to the docstrings for the functions being patched out here, so when folks go looking (or AI models take a look at the codebase) they can find the answer sooner.","path":"tests/conftest.py","line":99,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:37:59Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970693348"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"It wouldn't be too hard to make `open` return a fake file-like object (just an in-memory buffer) and then check that whatever was written into it deserializes to a copy of `test_data`, and that would be a much more useful test.","path":"tests/test_data.py","line":16,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:40:12Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970695129"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Yeah, it sure would be nice to test that the data can be round-tripped correctly! This test sure does not make any effort to verify that whatsoever.\n\n(I'll stop repeating this, you get the idea! please treat this as me being sarcastic at Claude and irritated at its poor output quality here, because that is indeed my attitude here)","path":"tests/test_data.py","line":42,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:43:20Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970697507"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This test could also be higher fidelity in fairly obvious ways.","path":"tests/test_data.py","line":84,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:45:01Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970698702"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"I am admittedly just skipping over this file -- I think the obvious \"did it do the thing?\" mocks are probably fine for this.","path":"tests/test_logging_utils.py","author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:46:53Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970700233"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"ಠ_ಠ","path":"tests/test_main.py","line":17,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:47:39Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970700713"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These don't seem useful.","path":"tests/test_main.py","line":27,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:47:58Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970700912"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"This might be useful? It will be mildly annoying if you deliberately change these things but useful if `setup` accidentally stops setting things up at all, so I guess this is probably fine?","path":"tests/test_main.py","line":40,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T02:49:09Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T03:07:05Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970701843"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"...Not off to a great start.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":1,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T03:34:43Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970760802"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"Oh, huh. That is important to keep in mind now that I see it -- it is _incorrect_ to create an AIAbstraction and then manually create a separate Player instance because the AIAbstraction instance has its own Player object that it expect to be associated with. Some of the prior advice I've given might be bad -- and this might have weird consequences for the half-fake half-mock things that might run into this.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":24,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T03:37:38Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970768635"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"These should of course be replaced by calls to `new_test_player` once it exists, but now I see that `new_test_player` needs to be more aware of how `AIAbstraction` actually works. Good to know, and the inconsistent construction story between \"human player\" and \"AI player\" probably needs a rethink longer-term but it's definitely out-of-scope here.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":26,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T03:42:24Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970780946"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"It's really weird that not only are both of these patched, they don't even agree. The rather heterogenous and uncontrolled data loading model of this code might force patching both, but the data disagreeing seems like a mistake.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":33,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T03:43:07Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970782858"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"To test an \"append\", we need to confirm that it is not a \"replace\". So this test needs to call `broadcast` again and make sure both messages are present for both AIs.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":115,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T03:57:19Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970828314"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"The test should know what these are, rather than having to recalculate. If it's more opinionated about the starting states...","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":126,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T04:01:53Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970840930"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"...it can also make stronger assertions here.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":131,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T04:02:07Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970841563"}],"total_count":1},{"is_resolved":false,"is_outdated":false,"is_collapsed":false,"comments":[{"body":"It's a little weird that you have to instantiate a `turn_manger` for this (of course, you already know how well it went when I had the same thought about `extract_choice`). This could _definitely_ have a lot more test cases and they would be easy to write -- it's a really good fit for `pytest.parametrize`. You could add tests for \"think tags exist with nothing between them\", \"unpaired think tags\", \"no think tags at all, but spare whitespace\", \"input is empty string\", \"input is only thinking\", etc.","path":"tests/classes/test_turnmanager_full.py","line":141,"author":"AdamNorberg","created_at":"2026-03-22T04:04:47Z","updated_at":"2026-03-22T05:09:27Z","html_url":"https://github.com/redisnotbluedev/discord-mafia/pull/29#discussion_r2970850482"}],"total_count":1}],"totalCount":123,"pageInfo":{"hasNextPage":true,"hasPreviousPage":false,"startCursor":"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wMy0yMVQxNjo0NzozNVrOdeVEzA==","endCursor":"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wMy0yMlQwNDowNDo0N1rOdfDctg=="}}